</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></code></pre></figure>]]></content><author><name></name></author><summary type="html"><![CDATA[combining fractals together]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Clark Quarry Paleoecology Project</title><link href="https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2025/Paleoecology-Project/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Clark Quarry Paleoecology Project"/><published>2025-10-20T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2025-10-20T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2025/Paleoecology-Project</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2025/Paleoecology-Project/"><![CDATA[<p>The College of Coastal Georgia (CCGA) has a small fossil lab where they study and classify microfossils from Clark Quarry, Brunswick, GA. I worked with Emma Robison, an environmental science student who is a member of the fossil lab. We took the lab’s data, calculated several biodiversity measures, and compared it with fossil data of the surrounding states. The estimated fossil deposition dates for Clark Quarry are of interest because they’re in the Late Pleistocene when many megafauna went extinct and overlaps with the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM).</p> <p>The poster was presented at the Georiga Resiliency Conference 2025 and is accepted to be presented at the American Geophysical Union conference in December 2025.</p> <p>There are many moving parts when studying the paleoclimate/ecology of the southeastern United States between 15-60 thousand years ago, and I’m grateful to have had the opportunity to work with the fossil lab.</p> <object data="/assets/pdf/GRC_Poster_Robison_Hutchinson.pdf" width="900" height="600" type="application/pdf"></object>]]></content><author><name></name></author><summary type="html"><![CDATA[some data analysis on fossils]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Sierpiński Carpet</title><link href="https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2025/sierpinski-carpet/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Sierpiński Carpet"/><published>2025-04-25T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2025-04-25T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2025/sierpinski-carpet</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2025/sierpinski-carpet/"><![CDATA[<div class="row"> <div class="col-md-6"> I submitted my poster project on the Sierpiński Carpet to the 2025 CCGA Endeavor Conference, and I was invited to give an oral presentation. I obliged, and gave a 10-minute presentation on April 24th (<a href="/assets/pdf/Endeavor%2010min%20Presentation.pptx">you can download the slides here</a>). Then on April 25th, I attended the poster session with my poster. The main goal was to get a handle on how to describe fractals mathematically, and I think the most satisfying answer was with Iterated Function Systems (IFS's). With the slideshow, I was able to animate the difference in constructing the Sierpiński Carpet with the usual deletion scheme versus the IFS. The Sierpiński Carpet is the unique fixed set under the IFS given in the poster. </div> <div class="col-md-5"> <img class="card-img" src="/assets/img/sierpinskiConference.jpg" alt="image"/> </div> </div> <object data="/assets/pdf/25-4-2025 sierpinski poster.pdf" width="900" height="600" type="application/pdf"></object>]]></content><author><name></name></author><summary type="html"><![CDATA[preliminary fractal study]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">BEER Poster</title><link href="https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2023/BEER-poster/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="BEER Poster"/><published>2023-11-03T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2023-11-03T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2023/BEER-poster</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://jamesmhutchinson.github.io/researchinterest/2023/BEER-poster/"><![CDATA[<p>I was fortunate enough to attend the CURE 2023 REU hosted by Illinois State University. After the experience, we picked advisors and made the below poster. It was a fun exercise in differential equations modeling, and it was presented at the 16th Annual International Symposium on Biomathematics and Ecology Education and Research (BEER) at Virginia Commonwealth University in November 2023, as well as the CCGA SOURCE conference in April 2024.</p> <object data="/assets/pdf/BEER_Poster.pdf" width="900" height="600" type="application/pdf"></object>]]></content><author><name></name></author><summary type="html"><![CDATA[modeling with differential equations]]></summary></entry></feed>